North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that the continuation of the sanctions was aggravating mistrust about the United States and that there was no way for the country to unilaterally renounce its nuclear weapons in those circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the world body’s annual General Assembly that North Korea had taken “significant goodwill measures” last year, such as the disruption of nuclear and missile tests, the dismantling of the nuclear test center and the commitment to non-proliferation of weapons and nuclear technologies.
"However, we see no corresponding response from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our national security and in such circumstances there is no way we can proceed to our disarmament first.”
Although Ri has recycled North Korean complaints already known about Washington's resistance to a "phased" approach to denuclearization, within which North Korea would be rewarded as it took step-by-step steps, his previous statements against Pyongyang appear to be significant insofar as unilaterally dismisses the licle.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first ever summit between a U.S. president and a North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work towards "denuclearization of the Korean peninsula," while Trump offered North Korea security assurances.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls for softening tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The United States insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases the level of pressure with sanctions to coercively achieve its goal, opposing even the ‘declaration of the end of war,’” Ri said.
“The perception that sanctions can put us on our knees is an impossible dream of people who know nothing about us.
However, the problem is that the extension of the sanctions is aggravating our distrust.”
Ri did not mention plans for the second summit between Kim and Trump that had been referred to by the U.S. leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister highlighted the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: "If South Korea were interested in this issue and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not have reached this impasse."
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was drastically different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly that directing North Korea’s rockets to U.S. territory was inevitable after “Mr. President Evil” Trump called Kim the “man of rockets” in a suicide mission.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year had threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, filled Kim with praise for his courage to take steps towards disarmament, but said there was still much to be done and that sanctions would have to continue until the denuclearization of North Korea.
