Harvard students attend a course that teaches them how to rest long enough
A new course at Harvard University this year put all of its students to sleep more, in an initiative to combat the machic culture of studying in caffeine-infused “directs.”
One professor concluded that the students of this university at the top of the world ranking often did not have the slightest idea about the most basic concepts about the care they should have with themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, was the author of the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
The inspiration for the course came after giving a lecture on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
"In the end, a girl came to me and said, 'Why are they just telling me this in the last year of the course?'
The young woman said that no one had ever mentioned the importance of sleep to her, which surprised me,” she told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts on how good sleep habits contribute positively to academic and athletic performance, as well as to the improvement of overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the institution decided to introduce the course after concluding that some students suffered from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The one-hour course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In a section there is an image of a dormitory where students click on coffee mugs, curtains, slippers and books to be informed about the effects of caffeine and light, and how athletic performance is influenced by sleep deficiency, and the importance of a routine to collect in bed.
In another section participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of stroke, depression and cancer.
Then, a map of the campus, with interactive icons, encourages participants to think about their daily routines.
“We know it won’t change the behavior of the students instantly.
However, we believe that they have the right to know, just as we all have the right to know the health effects of the smoking option,” added Professor Czeisler.
The culture of pride in “doing straight” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students makes this a growing problem.
Ensuring that we sleep enough and with quality should be a "secret weapon" for students to fight stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said, and even to avoid getting fat, as sleep deprivation puts the brain in a hunger mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student of physics and chemistry biology, helped Professor Czeisler devise the course after attending one of his classes last year in his first year at Harvard.
