Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that eventually led to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A fundamental piece of science since then, the accountant Geiger has also become a central element of pop culture, as in the 1950 film "Bells of Coronado" in which the unlikely cowboy scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans participated:
Man: "What the hell is that?"
Rogers: "It's a Geiger counter, used to locate radioactive minerals like uranium.
When we put on these headphones, we can even hear the effects of atoms released by radioactivity on minerals.”
Evans: "Look, now you're really cracking!"
"Hans" Geiger died in 1945, just days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that gave the name still persists.
