Red Tide Update: Concentrations Decline in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
According to new information from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission, there has been a decrease in Red Tide concentrations in some areas of Tampa Bay.
The FWC reported that conditions of lower proliferation of spots were identified in areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, suggesting a decrease in concentrations.
The red marsh stretches about 201 km along the coast, from Pinellas County to the north to Lee County to the south.
Spots can be found about 16 km off the coast of Hillsborough County, but in fewer areas than last week.
The Red Tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week, there were recorded mean concentrations near or off the coast of Pinella County, low to high concentrations off the coast of Hillsborough County, bottom to high concentrations in Manatee County, bottom to high concentrations near or off the coast of Sarasota County, bottom to middle concentrations.
There are still reports of respiratory irritation in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
Last week, there were no reports of respiratory irritation in the northwestern Florida region.
